owledge file.\n\nNow checking for any fabricated statements—the knowledge file's phrasing about building handler queues according to project requirements and potentially creating custom handlers aligns with what the source document says, just slightly reworded.\n\nLooking at the sync minimum handler configuration table, the process_stop_handler entry is mostly accurate but leaves out the detail that it specifically checks the request table's processing stop flag before throwing the exception. Looking at the source documentation more carefully, I can see the ProcessStop class reference is included in the full description, but the knowledge file's condensed version omits this detail entirely. It's a minor gap that loses some specificity about what exception gets thrown. Looking at the processing flow in s3, step 7 references `StatusCodeConvertHandler` but not `ProcessStop`, so those hints appear complete. Now checking s4's hints more carefully—I can see `thread_context_handler` is listed, but `thread_context_clear_handler` and `duplicate_process_check_handler` don't appear to be explicitly included in the hints array. I'm noticing that several handlers are actually present in the s4 section content but missing from the hints list — `thread_context_clear_handler`, `duplicate_process_check_handler`, `message_resend_handler`, and `ServiceAvailabilityCheckHandler` all appear in the handler list and relevant tables but weren't captured in the hints. For s5, the interface references like `DataReader`, `FwHeaderReader`, and `MessageReader` are properly documented in the hints. Now I'm moving on to check the section structure issues in the source document. The knowledge file organizes this into six sections, with the intro merged into the first one covering the MOM messaging structure. The s4 section contains the handler information along with its subsections about synchronous and asynchronous messaging configurations, all kept together rather than split out separately. Looki